rubric.evidence:
Real transformers.js generation in a dedicated module Worker (models/moondream2-vlm/worker.js): dynamic import of the pinned TRANSFORMERS_URL, then Moondream1ForConditionalGeneration.from_pretrained("Xenova/moondream2", {dtype:{embed_tokens:"fp16", vision_encoder:"fp16", decoder_model_merged:"q4f16"}, device:"webgpu"}) + AutoProcessor + AutoTokenizer. The worker builds Moondream's Q/A prompt frame `<image>

Question: ${prompt}

Answer:`, tokenises it, runs processor(image) for vision inputs, then model.generate({...inputs, do_sample:false, streamer: new TextStreamer(...)}) streams tokens back to the page via callback_function. This is a WebGPU-ONLY demo: worker probeGPU() calls navigator.gpu.requestAdapter() (presence is NOT enough) and createModelLoader is requiresWebGPU:true — on a no-GPU device (and in a no-GPU headless harness) the page shows a LABELLED needs-WebGPU state with enable steps, never a fabricated result. Because the GPU is genuinely unavailable in a no-GPU runner, the real-run output CANNOT be produced there and is NOT faked; the conformance runner records that class as blocked, not pass. Conformance asserts the mechanism: calls-real-inference (source, matches \.generate\() and loads-clean (console-clean) are tested-pass; io-shape-semantic is manual-evidenced.
